Excellent ‚Äî that output explains exactly why you‚Äôre seeing **‚Äúconnection refused.‚Äù**

Let‚Äôs break it down üëá

---

### üß© What‚Äôs happening

You currently have **two `kubectl port-forward` processes running**:

```
15138 ‚Üí svc/argocd-server 32063:443 --address=0.0.0.0
15364 ‚Üí service/argocd-server 8443:443   (default: localhost only)
```

‚úÖ **Process 15138** is correct ‚Äî it listens on all interfaces (`0.0.0.0`), meaning it can be reached via your EC2 public IP (`13.62.98.230:32063`).

‚ùå **Process 15364** is local-only (`127.0.0.1`), meaning it cannot be accessed from outside the EC2 instance.

---

### üß∞ What to do

Let‚Äôs clean this up and expose **one stable, accessible** port.

#### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Kill both running port-forward processes

```bash
sudo kill -9 15138 15364
```

---

#### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Start a new one that listens on all interfaces

```bash
kubectl port-forward -n argocd svc/argocd-server 8443:443 --address=0.0.0.0
```

‚úÖ You should see:

```
Forwarding from 0.0.0.0:8443 -> 8080
```

Keep this terminal **open** (don‚Äôt close or Ctrl+C).

---

#### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Verify it‚Äôs listening globally

Run:

```bash
sudo netstat -tulnp | grep 8443
```

Expected output:

```
tcp6   0   0 :::8443   :::*   LISTEN   <pid>/kubectl
```

---

#### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Then from your **local browser**, open:

üëâ **[https://13.62.98.230:8443](https://13.62.98.230:8443)**

Proceed past any SSL warning ‚Äî you should now see the **Argo CD login page** üéâ

---

If you still get ‚Äúrefused to connect,‚Äù please share the result of this command:

```bash
sudo netstat -tulnp | grep 8443
```

That will confirm whether the port is open for external access.






































